<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330A3195D82AFC3A174D" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" box="[151,945,800,827]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A3195D82AFEB2174C" bold="true" box="[151,313,800,826]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<typeStatus id="54F5BED8FFE3330A3195D82AFF5F174C" box="[151,212,800,826]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A3042D82BFD6B174D" authority="Fabricius, 1803" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1803" box="[320,736,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Lygaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicornis">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A3042D82BFD94174C" box="[320,543,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Lygaeus albicornis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF7D8BFFE3330A3325D82BFD6B174D" author="Fabricius" box="[551,736,801,827]" firstAuthor="Fabricius" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" refId="ref9075" refString="Fabricius, J. C. (1803) Systema Rhyngotorum secundum ordines, genera, species adjectis synonymis, locis, observationibus, descriptionibus. Carolum Reichert, Brunsvidae, x + 314 pp + 1 p [emendata]." type="book" year="1803">Fabricius, 1803</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Here designated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35453F1FFE3330931C7D84DFDB215B6" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330A31C7D84DFA961055" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A31C7D84DFED61717" bold="true" box="[197,349,839,865]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Description.</emphasis>
Colouration. Head mostly black (except of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A325ED842FB201714" authority="vinulus Stal, 1863" authorityName="vinulus Stal" authorityYear="1863" box="[860,1195,840,866]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="vinulus" subSpecies="vinulus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A325ED842FBA41717" box="[860,1071,840,865]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">D. vinulus vinulus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF7D8BFFE3330A3537D842FB201714" author="Stal" box="[1077,1195,840,866]" firstAuthor="Stal" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="390 - 404" refId="ref9552" refString="Stal, C. (1863) Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Pyrrhocoriden. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift, 7, 390 - 404." type="journal article" year="1863">Stål, 1863</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with anterior part of head red, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A303CD865FD2717FE" authority="Stehlik &amp; Jindra, 2008" authorityName="Stehlik &amp; Jindra" authorityYear="2008" box="[318,684,878,904]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stysi">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A303CD865FED817FE" box="[318,339,879,904]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A3061D865FE1C17FE" box="[355,407,879,904]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">stysi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF7D8BFFE3330A309DD864FD2717FE" author="Stehlik &amp; Jindra" box="[415,684,878,904]" firstAuthor="Stehlik" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="611 - 648" refId="ref10087" refString="Stehlik, J. L. &amp; Jindra, Z. (2008) New taxa of Largidae and Pyrrhocoridae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera) from Oriental region. Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 48, 611 - 648." type="journal article" year="2008">Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with entire head bright red). Pronotum black, pronotal margins often creamy white, in two species posterior pronotal margin with two yellow spots medially. Anterior part of hemelytra black, posterior part usually red (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A33BAD8B6FBF917A0" authority="Stehlik &amp; Jindra, 2006" authorityName="Stehlik &amp; Jindra" authorityYear="2006" box="[696,1138,956,982]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talaudensis">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A33BAD8B6FD4617A3" box="[696,717,956,981]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A33DED8B6FCEA17A3" box="[732,865,956,981]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">talaudensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF7D8BFFE3330A326BD8B6FBF917A0" author="Stehlik &amp; Jindra" box="[873,1138,956,982]" firstAuthor="Stehlik" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="21 - 30" refId="ref9981" refString="Stehlik, J. L. &amp; Jindra, Z. (2006) Five new species of the genus Dindymus (Heteroptera: Pyrrhocoridae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 46, 21 - 30." type="journal article" year="2006">Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2006</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
entire clavus and corium red), less frequently posterior part of hemelytra whitish. Pleura I–III ventrally black; prosternal collar, posterior pleural flanges I–III, and epicoxal lobes usually yellowish white. Abdomen ventrally red.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330A31C7DF3AFD6A1006" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Punctation prominent only on pronotal lobe, its intensity differing among species; clavus and corium with dense fine punctation; sternum without punctures.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330A31C7DF77FBD4112E" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Structure. Eyes protruding, quite remote from anterior pronotal margin and distinctly surpassing it laterally. Posterior part of head never markedly elongated. Anterior portion of pronotum narrowed. Lateral pronotal margin rather wide, elevated dorsally, distinctly concave at level of median furrow. Callar lobe gibbous, without anteromedian protuberances (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A33F2DFFBFCE7117C" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1863" box="[752,876,1265,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vinulus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A33F2DFFBFCE7117C" box="[752,876,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">D. vinulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with median furrow indicated only medially). Pronotal lobe gibbous towards base. Costal margin of hemelytra somewhat insinuated behind base, rather wide in the rest of its length. Mesoscutum depressed, scutellum markedly gibbous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330A31C7DE6FFCAB12C2" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Pygophore. Ventral rim always with two median processes of variable shape: flat, with inner side concave, or in form of a blunted cone. Other parts of ventral and lateral rim rounded, straight. Ventral rim infolding wide, only slightly sloping into genital chamber, continually merging into dish-shaped lateral rim infolding; lower margin of lateral rim infolding elevated dorsally just behind the transition of ventral rim infolding and forming a projection. Anal tube rather long. Parameres small, never crossed (e.g., 
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE3330A3576DD0AFAA9126C" box="[1140,1314,1536,1562]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="6.[151,272,992,1016]" captionTargetBox="[224,1362,194,962]" captionTargetId="figure-292@6.[224,1362,194,968]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Pygophore, dorsal view. 7—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803), Malaysia: Sabah; 8—D. (P.) pulcher Stål, 1863, Philippines: Luzon; 9—D. (P.) daiacus Breddin, 1901, Philippines: Palawan); 10—D. (P.) sandakan sp. nov., paratype, Malaysia: Sabah; 11—D. (P.) vinulus vinulus Stål, 1863, Philippines: Mindanao; 12—D. (Dindymus) rubiginosus (Fabricius, 1787), Laos." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Figs. 8, 10 
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A35F1DD0AFA89126F" box="[1267,1282,1536,1561]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">–</emphasis>
11
</figureCitation>
). Processi hamati of parameres acicular, sometimes positioned horizontally against each other and considerably distant, or processi hamati somewhat elevated dorsally and distant or approached, respectively. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A35BEDD47FECA12F8" authority="Breddin, 1901" authorityName=": Breddin" authorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbaticollis" subGenus="Pseudodindymus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A35BEDD47FB521210" box="[1212,1241,1613,1638]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">D.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A35E1DD47FB721210" box="[1251,1273,1613,1638]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A340BDD47FA171210" box="[1289,1436,1613,1638]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">limbaticollis</emphasis>
Breddin, 1901
</taxonomicName>
, processus hamatus is completely missing and the short paramere body is visible only in lateral corners of genital chamber (near ventral rim infolding).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE3330931C7DDCBFAA01550" blockId="1.[151,1437,800,2026]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,1222]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Phallus (detailed description: 
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE3330A333ADDCBFC9D12AC" box="[568,790,1729,1754]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
D. a. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE3330A337DDDCBFD7D12AC" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1803" box="[639,758,1729,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Lygaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicornis">albicornis</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE3330A3214DDCBFCD412AD" box="[790,863,1729,1755]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, in remaining examined species the phallus is similar). Vesica short, strongly sclerotized, basally and subapically thickened, medially attenuated, apex of vesica in lateral view strongly narrowed, slightly curved, secondary gonopore horizontally positioned (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE3330A3444DC04FA06135E" box="[1350,1421,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Conjunctival processes 1 parallel on both sides of vesica, basally attenuated, its lateral margin medially convex, apex attenuated, blunt, strongly sclerotized, black, ca. reaching height of vesica. Conjunctival processes 2 originating near base of vesica, directed laterad, basally weakly sclerotized, slender, slightly thickened medially, apically narrowed and curved ventrally. Two short, robust, conical, apically rounded, more sclerotized, and blackened projections situated near base of vesica between conjunctival processes 2. Conjunctival processes 3 originating laterally on conjunctiva, very wide, strongly narrowing towards apex, apex blunt, anterior part and apex well-sclerotized. Hind wall of conjunctiva behind vesica with large semicircular conjunctival collar (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE0330930EADBEFFDBB1489" box="[488,560,229,255]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), its margins strongly sclerotized, with pair of large, strongly sclerotized, posteriorly curved, blunt projections situated in their lateral thirds. Basal part of conjunctiva simple.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE0330931C7DA38FDB215B6" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,1222]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Outer female genitalia rather uniform with only slight interspecific variability. Both sides of valvifer I arcuatelly gaping open near base, their margin markedly depressed in the place of gaping in all included species. Valvifer II medially connate, flat, not very long, with two differently shaped protuberances. Anal tube short, embraced by laterotergite IX.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35453F1FFE0330931C7DAC7FB2D17E6" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE0330931C7DAC7FB2D17E6" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,1222]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330931C7DAC7FE681591" bold="true" box="[197,483,461,487]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE0330930EEDAC7FD321590" box="[492,697,461,486]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Pseudodindymus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330930EEDAC7FD321590" box="[492,697,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pseudodindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330933C1DAC7FCE91591" bold="true" box="[707,866,461,487]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE0330933C1DAC7FCE91591" box="[707,866,461,487]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is defined especially by the ventral rim of the pygophore always with two median processes, and parameres never crossing each other (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE0330935EFDAFEFAC11678" box="[1261,1354,500,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="6.[151,272,992,1016]" captionTargetBox="[224,1362,194,962]" captionTargetId="figure-292@6.[224,1362,194,968]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Pygophore, dorsal view. 7—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803), Malaysia: Sabah; 8—D. (P.) pulcher Stål, 1863, Philippines: Luzon; 9—D. (P.) daiacus Breddin, 1901, Philippines: Palawan); 10—D. (P.) sandakan sp. nov., paratype, Malaysia: Sabah; 11—D. (P.) vinulus vinulus Stål, 1863, Philippines: Mindanao; 12—D. (Dindymus) rubiginosus (Fabricius, 1787), Laos." pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
, white arrow). The phallus of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE0330930F4D910FD451645" box="[502,718,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Pseudodindymus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330930F4D910FD451645" box="[502,718,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pseudodindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330933DBD910FC091642" bold="true" box="[729,898,538,564]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE0330933DBD910FC091642" box="[729,898,538,564]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is markedly smaller and differs from the nominotypical subgenus in the following characters: i) conjunctival process 1 short, not surpassing vesica, not sharply pointed (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE03309305DD962FE2E16F4" box="[351,421,616,642]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); ii) conjunctival process 2 shorter, apically strongly curved, not originating from the base of the conjunctival process 1; iii) conjunctival process 4 not developed, replaced by semi-circular conjunctival collar (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE033093083D9BFFE4C16B9" box="[385,455,693,719]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); and iv) lacking conjunctival process 
<quantity id="4CB6AD9FFFE033093289D9BFFC3316B9" box="[907,952,693,719]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
basal part of conjunctiva. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE03309340ED9BFFA0916B8" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1861" box="[1292,1410,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE03309340ED9BFFA0916B8" box="[1292,1410,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Dindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE03309348BD9BFFF311680" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
i) the conjunctival process 1 is long, markedly surpassing vesica, sharply pointed (
<figureCitation id="13751CFFFFE033093588D9D6FB591680" box="[1162,1234,732,758]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[330,1298,198,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-63@4.[275,1322,183,1901]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1–3—Dindymus (Pseudodindymus) albicornis albicornis (Fabricius, 1803). 1—phallus; 2—vesica (lateral view); 3—semi-circular conjunctival collar on the hind wall of conjunctiva. 4—Dindymus (Dindymus) brevis Blöte, 1931, phallus. Abbreviations: CC—conjunctival collar, CJ—conjunctiva, CJPR—conjunctival processes, S—sclerite; SG—secondary gonopore; V—vesica." pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); ii) conjunctival process 2 originating from base of the conjunctival process 1, longer, apically straight; iii) conjunctival processes 4 and 5 well developed. Phalli of all the species included in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE033093504D823FB461734" box="[1030,1229,809,834]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Pseudodindymus">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE033093504D823FB461734" box="[1030,1229,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pseudodindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330935D7D822FAE41734" bold="true" box="[1237,1391,808,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE0330935D7D822FAE41734" box="[1237,1391,808,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are very similar, supporting the monophyly of this taxon, while in species-rich 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE033093543D85AFB37171F" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1861" box="[1089,1212,848,873]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE033093543D85AFB37171F" box="[1089,1212,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Dindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE0330935C4D85AFA8C171C" box="[1222,1287,848,874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
some small modifications exist. For detailed description of the phallus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E7BF9FFE03309326BD87DFC6B17E6" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1861" box="[873,992,887,912]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrrhocoridae" genus="Dindymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE03309326BD87DFC6B17E6" box="[873,992,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Dindymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2096113FFE0330932EAD87CFBAE17E6" box="[1000,1061,886,912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
see below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35453F1FFE0330931C7D897FADA100E" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF1007AFFE0330931C7D897FE9F17A8" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,1222]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B93ADC68FFE0330931C7D897FED917C1" bold="true" box="[197,338,925,951]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</emphasis>
